      <hedline>
        <hl1>On the Playing Field, Boys Still Go First</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>California Women's Law Center executive director Abby J Feibman letter, prompted by Aug 20 article on women moving closer to Olympic equality, asks how glory of Olympic Games can co-exist with discrimination that has occurred against women athletes in California; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Women Move Closer to Olympic Equality'' (front page, Aug. 20):</p>
        <p>Title IX, which bans sex discrimination in federally financed programs, opened many doors to American women and girls in sports, but its promise has only begun to be realized.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Women Move Closer to Olympic Equality'' (front page, Aug. 20):</p>
        <p>Title IX, which bans sex discrimination in federally financed programs, opened many doors to American women and girls in sports, but its promise has only begun to be realized.</p>
        <p>California, home to so many star athletes, is also home to some of the most egregious discrimination. In Los Angeles, only 20 percent of participants in city parks and recreation programs were girls until a lawsuit sparked greater outreach by the city.</p>
        <p>In Riverside County, the boys' Little League teams were provided with uniforms, regularly scheduled practice times, reserved fields and experienced umpires calling their games. The girls' teams were not. How can the glory of the Olympic Games co-exist with such startling examples of discrimination?</p>
        <p>ABBY J. LEIBMAN  Los Angeles, Aug. 23, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is executive director of the California Women's Law Center.</p>
      </block>
